	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Southern Africa trade policy: SADC’s trade performance reviewed</h1>

			
			<h4>
												10 June 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A World Bank research paper was published in April on ‘Trends in intra-regional and extra-regional trade flows and policy’ in the SADC region. The paper concluded that while SADC ‘has continued to experience a decline in its share of world trade over the past decade and a half’, as the region’s share of ‘developing country real exports fell from 7.1 to 2.9 percent’, SADC countries ‘have experienced an increase in openness that is comparable to other developing countries’. Furthermore, the paper found that ‘once market size and geography are taken into account, trade between SADC countries is actually high.’ However, after increasing during the 1990s, the expansion of intra-regional trade has ‘slowed recently’.</p><p>SADC is described as being ‘quite integrated’. While tariff reductions have taken place, the tariff structure ‘remains complex and could be lowered’. There is also seen to be scope for the removal of other trade impediments, although these are currently ‘at levels that are comparable with countries at similar levels of development’.</p><p>Within SADC, ‘Malawi, Mozambique, Zambia and Zimbabwe depend heavily upon SADC, particularly for imports’, sourcing more than 50% of imports and trading more than 20% of exports into regional markets. Other SADC countries ‘maintain much stronger trade relationships with the rest of the world’. The paper notes that ‘substantial asymmetries in trade flows persist.’ South Africa is central to regional trade flows, with between 60 and 70% of SADC exports to the region sold into SACU markets, and 80 to 90% of SADC imports from the region coming from the SACU countries.</p><p>The paper notes that ‘products that make up a high proportion of exports to the SADC area often make up only a small proportion of the country’s exports to the rest of the world’, with SADC countries exporting ‘different products to different countries’. In addition, ‘many SADC countries export a more diverse range of products to the SADC region than to the rest of the world.’</p><p>The paper concludes that ‘the SADC region now faces a trade policy environment that is more conducive towards promoting intra- and extra-regional trade flows and product market integration.’ Overall it is argued that ‘SADC’s trade performance is not particularly bad and its trade policy is not necessarily deficient.’</p><p>An ISS paper published in March similarly found that membership of SADC ‘significantly increases bilateral trade flows’. Indeed, it went further, arguing that SADC membership had more of an impact in increasing bilateral trade flows ‘than for example preferential trade agreements with the EU do’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
World Bank Group, ‘How integrated is SADC? Trends in intra-regional and extra-regional trade flows and policy’, WPS5625, April 2011 <br/>

<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/Behar&amp;Edward_EN_01042011_WB_How%20integrated%20is%20SADC.pdf" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/Behar&amp;Edward_EN_01042011_W...</a><br/>
International Institute of Social Studies (ISS), ‘Multi-membership and the effectiveness of regional trade agreements in Western and Southern Africa: A comparative study of ECOWAS and SADC’, Working Paper No. 520, March 2011<br/>
<a href="http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/Afesorgbor&amp;%20Bergeijk_EN_010411_IISS_Multi-membership%20and%20the%20effectiveness%20of%20regional%20trade%20.pdf" target="_self">http://www.acp-eu-trade.org/library/files/Afesorgbor&amp;%20Bergeijk_EN_...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>It is unclear to what extent the high dependence of land-locked countries such as Malawi, Zambia and Zimbabwe on intra-SADC trade reflects the re-export and transit trade which takes place via South Africa. Food and agricultural products are particularly dependent on intra-SADC trade, as the distribution and retail networks are focused on South Africa and dominate intra-regional trade, and consolidated consignments traded on an intra-corporate basis play a major role in trade flows.</p><p>This situation raises important rules-of-origin questions under preferential trade agreements. Within SADC, duty-free trade is now the rule. In this context, for some food and agricultural products destined for some southern African markets (e.g. butter to Zimbabwe), it can make commercial sense to import in bulk and repackage in South Africa prior to onward export, thereby circumventing import duties which would have been charged on, for example, EU butter. The proliferation of EPA agreements with different tariff-elimination commitments within the SADC region could potentially exacerbate this situation and give rise to trade diversion.</p><p>So long as the volumes involved are small this is unlikely to pose major problems. However, given the size of many local markets in the SADC region, even relatively small volumes (in terms of overall EU exports) could have significant market disruption effects.</p><p>Equally, within SADC in the food and agricultural sector, a range of trade policy tools are used to regulate market access so as to encourage local production. Prohibiting or reducing the use of these trade policy tools could prove difficult given shortcomings in the functioning of supply chains in the region, arising from the growing economic dominance of South African distribution and retail networks in a number of SADC member states.</p>
		</div>
		
